9.30am West Indies are in the field, here come Lee and Casson and we're ready to start.

9.25am Hello and welcome to the second day of this third Test in Barbados, where West Indies will be aiming for a quick three wickets. Australia's lower order, meanwhile, can build the score up into the high 200s if they build a couple of useful partnerships, so it's an important session coming up. The good news is that despite some rain we are expecting an on-time start.

5.00pm There's no easy way to say this, but play has been abandoned for the day. The second day will start half an hour earlier tomorrow so do join us at 2.30pm. Thanks for following today and thanks for your patience through the rain delay. It's been an interesting day, right from the point when Chris Gayle won the toss and sent Australia in. There were thrills - in the form of plenty of sixes in the opening session - and spills - the odd hard chance spilled - and plenty of wickets and runs. All in all a great day's cricket and West Indies have grabbed the honours. Thank you for joining myself Jenny Roesler and himself Jamie Alter today, do come back tomorrow.

4.45pm Ah, news! An inspection is due in half an hour, so that's something. If you're just joining us, welcome to coverage of West Indies against Australia, the third Test from Barbados. You've missed a cracker of a day so far and we're currently in the middle of a rain delay. I'm afraid it's looking very murky out there.

4.40pm More rain. Sigh. Meanwhile Avinash Mangar has a big can labelled "Worms" and he's not afraid to open it. "I really don't see what the big deal about counties signing Kolpaks is. Clubs have to be competitive in order to even field England-qualified players, and Kolpaks allow the smaller clubs (Leicestershire) to do so." Hmm. Andrew Pearson emails: "Now that Twenty20 is established, anybody offering odds on international French cricket?" Well, beach cricket has also been popularised in Australia with Lillee, Hadlee, Thommo, Gooch etc, so you never know...although I think you can guess.

4.20pm Still raining, curses. Please hold the line. Please hold the line. Your readership is important to us. Etc. Here is Stuart Francis: "I seem to remember Steve Harmison had a sort of beard for a while." True. Plenty of emails in commending Malcolm Marshall and WG Grace. Still no word on start time, either. Very frustrating when we had been enjoying a good day's cricket with West Indies challenging Australia. They will be particularly annoyed as they are, of course, aiming to level the series.

Have you checked out our gallery or Brydon's bulletin both regarding this match?

Also, are you fully up to speed on the latest Allen Stanford developments? Read all about it here and here. More news from England concerns the possible end of Kolpaks in county cricket.

Drop us a line if you feel strongly about any of the above issues.

4.05pm No, no. It's raining again. Sorry about that, folks. Cameron emails: "Jason Gillespie had a beard. And then there was Merv Hughes, whose moustache almost qualified as a beard." Good point. Farhan adds: "Curtley Ambrose usually sported a light beard. (I don't know what to call it)." Me neither, but I know what you mean. Loving the use of "sporting" there, also.

3.50pm Right, the umpires are in the middle having a conflab. It looks like the light may be the issue, we're not fully sure so don't quote us, but hope to have some confirmation soon. The rope is going round so they are trying to get some water off the surface. We've just heard that play should resume at 4.10pm.

3.40pm And indeed the players dash off as the covers are hurried on. Most annoying having had some entertaining cricket up until now. "Rain, rain go away" is buzzing through my head; the Kanye version on Family Business. Hopefully this will be a quick shower. Plenty of emails in support of Hashim Amla's beard, too. So, then, you've read the news on the site today, have you checked out our blogs recently? Meanwhile, Harris in the US has a poser: "Why do fast bowlers not have beards?" Anyone?
